AssociationRules.mappers

Class CandidateMapper

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.apache.hadoop.mapreduce.Mapper<java.lang.Object,org.apache.hadoop.io.Text,org.apache.hadoop.io.Text,org.apache.hadoop.io.IntWritable>
      • AssociationRules.mappers.CandidateMapper

  • public class CandidateMapper
extends org.apache.hadoop.mapreduce.Mapper<java.lang.Object,org.apache.hadoop.io.Text,org.apache.hadoop.io.Text,org.apache.hadoop.io.IntWritable>
    CandidateMapper is the mapper used for the frequent itemset extraction. The class handles the extraction of itemsets with a fixed length from an input basket.

    It relies on the following job configurations:

    • TUPEL_SIZE: the size of the itemsets that are going to be extracted from a basket
    • TMP_FILE_PATH: the file system location, where the intermediary files are to be found
    • BASKET_ITEM_SPLITTER: the character sequence that separates items in the input basket

    The mapper will attempt to load the following files, but doesn't rely on them. The whitelist e.g. is not supposed to exist when the TUPEL_SIZE is equal 1.

    • item-keyMap.ser: the map serialization of the item names to integer key mapping
    • key-itemMap.ser: the map serialization of the integer keys to item name mapping
    • whitelist_x_tupel.ser: x is the current TUPEL_SIZE-1, the file contains the BitSet representation of the previous frequent itemsets
    Since:
    1.0

      • map

        public void map(java.lang.Object key,
                org.apache.hadoop.io.Text value,
                org.apache.hadoop.mapreduce.Mapper.Context context)
         throws java.io.IOException,
                java.lang.InterruptedException
        Parses an input basket into the distinct items, translates them to integer keys and writes a count of one for each subset of a given size. The mapper will take an input basket (the value) and split it at the specified delimiter into distinct items. If the number of items in the basket is greater or equal to the current tupel size, the mapper will translate all items to integer values with mappings from the file or with a newly created mapping. The mapper will then generate all subsets of size equal to the current tupel size and write a count of one to the context.

        INPUT FORMAT

        key : lineidentifier
        value: basket, e.g. A,B,C,D

        OUTPUT FORMAT

        key : Itemset, e.g. 1;2;3
        value: 1 (count is always 1 ;) )

        Overrides:
        map in class org.apache.hadoop.mapreduce.Mapper<java.lang.Object,org.apache.hadoop.io.Text,org.apache.hadoop.io.Text,org.apache.hadoop.io.IntWritable>
        Parameters:
        key - a input file lineidentifier
        value - the concatenated itemset-count pair
        context - the context of the map reduce job
        Throws:
        java.io.IOException - is called in a file system context
        java.lang.InterruptedException - executed as thread, therefore can be interrupted
        See Also:
        Utils.getSubsets(List, int), Utils.concatenateArray(Integer[], String)
